abstract: Taiwan prosecutors say they have detained 10 people, including a former staff member of the China-friendly opposition party, and are investigating them on suspicion of falsifying documents to bring thousands of mainland Chinese to Taiwan, possibly including some who spied on the self-ruled island claimed by Beijing.
snippet: Taiwan prosecutors say they have detained 10 people, including a former staff member of the China-friendly opposition party, and are investigating them on suspicion of falsifying documents to bring thousands of mainland Chinese to Taiwan, possibly...
lead_paragraph: TAIPEI, Taiwan — Taiwan prosecutors say they have detained 10 people, including a former staff member of the China-friendly opposition party, and are investigating them on suspicion of falsifying documents to bring thousands of mainland Chinese to Taiwan, possibly including some who spied on the self-ruled island claimed by Beijing.
headline_main: Taiwan Probes Visa Scam Allowing Visits by Chinese Officials
headline_print_headline: Taiwan Probes Visa Scam Allowing Visits by Chinese Officials

abstract: Britain’s prime minister has hitched his re-election campaign to a promise to “get Brexit done.” But he’s selling bankers and blue-collar workers two very different visions for the country.

abstract: Charlize Theron, Nicole Kidman and Margot Robbie star in a story about the fall of Roger Ailes.
snippet: Charlize Theron, Nicole Kidman and Margot Robbie star in a story about the fall of Roger Ailes.
lead_paragraph: Bright and bouncy until it turns grim, “Bombshell” is a fictionalized account of the women who brought down Roger Ailes, the chairman and chief executive of Fox News. Helped bring him down is probably more accurate given that he was ousted by Rupert Murdoch, who founded Fox News in 1996 before handing the reins to Ailes. Since then, the network has become a ratings powerhouse and hothouse of right-wing talking points, a sea of white faces and dolled-up women in skirts and high heels. Ailes is now gone but the talking points, high ratings, skirts and heels remain.

abstract: The only thing necessary for bigots to be normalized is for the unbigoted to shrug.

lead_paragraph: Back when Donald Trump was running for president — and Republicans were still capable of feeling politically ashamed — a conservative friend made what was, to my mind, the decisive case against voting for him.

abstract: As the country heads for yet another divisive election, it’s time to address the roots of our crisis.
snippet: As the country heads for yet another divisive election, it’s time to address the roots of our crisis.
lead_paragraph: It’s official. Israel will hold another election in March, our third national vote in less than 12 months. With trust in Israeli political parties already at a historic low, this election will only reinforce how broken Israeli politics have become.

abstract: Crime, economic stagnation and erratic government decisions signal a long and bumpy ride for his presidency — and his country.
snippet: Crime, economic stagnation and erratic government decisions signal a long and bumpy ride for his presidency — and his country.
lead_paragraph: So the first year of Andrés Manuel López Obrador’s presidency of Mexico has come and gone, and there is both much and little to say about it. While no major catastrophe has come to pass, a bright new future seems more distant than ever. He is cruising, but his results are desultory.

abstract: Britain's election campaign has delivered funny, strange and surreal moments, from Prime Minister Boris Johnson's Brexit-branded boxing to a stranded train full of journalists on their way to a speech about rail investment.

lead_paragraph: LONDON — Britain's election campaign has delivered funny, strange and surreal moments, from Prime Minister Boris Johnson's Brexit-branded boxing to a stranded train full of journalists on their way to a speech about rail investment.

abstract: Cambodia's government said on Thursday it had responded to the European Union over human rights and political concerns and urged the bloc to consider that nearly one million female workers would be affected if it suspended trade benefits.
snippet: Cambodia's government said on Thursday it had responded to the European Union over human rights and political concerns and urged the bloc to consider that nearly one million female workers would be affected if it suspended trade benefits.
lead_paragraph: PHNOM PENH — Cambodia's government said on Thursday it had responded to the European Union over human rights and political concerns and urged the bloc to consider that nearly one million female workers would be affected if it suspended trade benefits.
headline_main: Cambodia Says Responds to EU Over Human Rights Concern
headline_print_headline: Cambodia Says Responds to EU Over Human Rights Concern
